CRISP-DM (Cross Industry Standard Process for Data Mining)¶

1.Business Understanding¶

  • What are the main federal highways?
  • On which road do most accidents happen?
  • What is the type of accident that happens the most?
  • What month of the year has the most accidents?
  • What time of day does most accidents happen?
  • On which holiday does the most accident happen?
  • In which km does the most accident happen on each road?

2.Data understanding¶

Open data from the Federal Government of Brazil recording accidents that occurred on federal highways.

https://www.gov.br/prf/pt-br/acesso-a-informacao/dados-abertos/dados-abertos-da-prf

In [14]:
# Dead victims or serious injuries will be graded as higher severity
def serious(df):               
    if df['mortos'] > 0:
        return 1
    if df['feridos_graves'] > 0:
        return 1
    else:
        return 0
    
new_df['serious'] = new_df.apply(serious, axis=1)

In [16]:
new_df['dia'] = new_df['data_inversa'].apply(lambda x: x[-2:]) # Day
new_df['mes'] = new_df['data_inversa'].apply(lambda x: x[-5:-3]) # Month
new_df['ano'] = new_df['data_inversa'].apply(lambda x: x[:-6]) # Year
In [17]:
# Identifying the dates that are national holidays in Brazil

# Holidays that always fall on the same date
c_universal = '01-01'
tiradentes = '04-21'
dm_trabalho = '05-01'
independencia = '09-07'
ns_aparecida = '10-12'
s_publico = '10-28'
finados = '11-02'
p_republica = '11-15'
v_natal = '12-24'
natal = '12-25'
a_novo = '12-31'

# Holidays that fall on different dates each year
carnaval21 = ['15', '16', '17'] # Month 02
carnaval20 = ['24', '25', '26'] # Month 02
carnaval19 = ['04', '05', '06'] # Month 03

paixaocristo21 = '02' # Month 04
paixaocristo20 = '10' # Month 04
paixaocristo19 = '19' # Month 04

corpuschristi21 = '03' # Month 06
corpuschristi20 = '11' # Month 06
corpuschristi19 = '20' # Month 06

def holiday(new_df):
    if new_df['mes'] == '01':
        if new_df['dia'] == c_universal[-2:]:
            return 'c_universal'
    if new_df['mes'] == '02':
        if new_df['ano'] == '21':
            if new_df['dia'] in carnaval21:
                return 'carnaval'
        if new_df['ano'] == '20':
            if new_df['dia'] in carnaval20:
                return 'carnaval'
    if new_df['mes'] == '03':
        if new_df['ano'] == '20':
            if new_df['dia'] in carnaval19:
                return 'carnaval'    
    if new_df['mes'] == '04':
        if new_df['dia'] == tiradentes[-2:]:
            return 'tiradentes'
        if new_df['ano'] == '21':
            if new_df['dia'] == paixaocristo21[-2:]:
                return 'paixaocristo'
        if new_df['ano'] == '20':
            if new_df['dia'] == paixaocristo20[-2:]:
                return 'paixaocristo'
        if new_df['ano'] == '19':
            if new_df['dia'] == paixaocristo19[-2:]:
                return 'paixaocristo'    
    if new_df['mes'] == '05':
        if new_df['dia'] == dm_trabalho[-2:]:
            return 'dm_trabalho'     
    if new_df['mes'] == '06':
        if new_df['ano'] == '21':
            if new_df['dia'] == corpuschristi21[-2:]:
                return 'corpuschristi'
        if new_df['ano'] == '20':
            if new_df['dia'] == corpuschristi20[-2:]:
                return 'corpuschristi'
        if new_df['ano'] == '19':
            if new_df['dia'] == corpuschristi19[-2:]:
                return 'corpuschristi'    
    if new_df['mes'] == '09':
        if new_df['dia'] == independencia[-2:]:
            return 'independencia'
    if new_df['mes'] == '10':
        if new_df['dia'] == ns_aparecida[-2:]:
            return 'ns_aparecida'
        if new_df['dia'] == s_publico[-2:]:
            return 's_publico'        
    if new_df['mes'] == '11':
        if new_df['dia'] == finados[-2:]:
            return 'finados'
        if new_df['dia'] == p_republica[-2:]:
            return 'p_republica'       
    if new_df['mes'] == '12':
        if new_df['dia'] == v_natal[-2:]:
            return 'v_natal'
        if new_df['dia'] == natal[-2:]:
            return 'natal'
        if new_df['dia'] == a_novo[-2:]:
            return 'a_novo'
        else:
            return 'normal_day'
    else: 
        return 'normal_day'
    
new_df['holiday'] = new_df.apply(holiday, axis=1)

# Identifying the weekends
def weekend(new_df):
    if new_df['dia_semana'] in ['sábado', 'domingo']:
        return 'weekend'
    else:
        return 'weekday'
    
new_df['week'] = new_df.apply(weekend, axis=1)

# Divide the day into 24 hours
def hour(new_df): 
    if datetime.strptime('00:00:00', '%H:%M:%S') <= datetime.strptime(new_df['horario'], '%H:%M:%S') <= datetime.strptime('00:59:59', '%H:%M:%S'):
        return '00:00:00'
    if datetime.strptime('01:00:00', '%H:%M:%S') <= datetime.strptime(new_df['horario'], '%H:%M:%S') <= datetime.strptime('01:59:59', '%H:%M:%S'):
        return '01:00:00'
    if datetime.strptime('02:00:00', '%H:%M:%S') <= datetime.strptime(new_df['horario'], '%H:%M:%S') <= datetime.strptime('02:59:59', '%H:%M:%S'):
        return '02:00:00'      
    if datetime.strptime('03:00:00', '%H:%M:%S') <= datetime.strptime(new_df['horario'], '%H:%M:%S') <= datetime.strptime('03:59:59', '%H:%M:%S'):
        return '03:00:00'
    if datetime.strptime('04:00:00', '%H:%M:%S') <= datetime.strptime(new_df['horario'], '%H:%M:%S') <= datetime.strptime('04:59:59', '%H:%M:%S'):
        return '04:00:00'
    if datetime.strptime('05:00:00', '%H:%M:%S') <= datetime.strptime(new_df['horario'], '%H:%M:%S') <= datetime.strptime('05:59:59', '%H:%M:%S'):
        return '05:00:00'
    if datetime.strptime('06:00:00', '%H:%M:%S') <= datetime.strptime(new_df['horario'], '%H:%M:%S') <= datetime.strptime('06:59:59', '%H:%M:%S'):
        return '06:00:00'

The data are for 2019, 2020 and 2021: https://www.gov.br/prf/pt-br/acesso-a-informacao/dados-abertos/dados-abertos-acidentes

Of the federal highways that pass through the Federal District, four have a significant number of accidents:

  • BR 020
  • BR 040
  • BR 060
  • BR 070

Period with the highest number of victims in serious condition and/or deaths:

  • Weekend with public holiday

BR and month with the highest number of accidents:

  • BR 20 = December > October > September > February
  • BR 40 = August > September > July > October
  • BR 60 = December > September > June e February
  • BR 70 = Showed little oscillation. Keeping an average always high.

The BR 40 had the highest number of accidents. Followed by BR 20 and then BR 70

Most critical point in each BR:

  • BR 20 = KM 9
  • BR 251 = KM 32
  • BR 40 = KM 5
  • BR 50 = KM 96
  • BR 60 = KM 4
  • BR 70 = KM 9
  • BR 80 = KM 25.

Most frequent type of accident in each BR:

  • BR 20 = Rear collision
  • BR 251 = Cross collision
  • BR 40 = Rear collision
  • BR 50 = Exit from the carousel bed
  • BR 60 = Exit from the carousel bed
  • BR 70 = Rear collision
  • BR 80 = Exit from the carousel bed

The holiday with the most accidents:

  • 1st - 'Confraternização Universal'
  • 2nd - 'Tiradentes'
  • 3rd - 'Independência'
  • 4th - 'Finados'
  • 5th - 'Trabalho'
  • 6th - 'Nossa Senhora Aparecida'
  • 7th - 'Proclamação da República'
  • 8th - 'Véspera de Natal'
  • 9th - 'Ano Novo'
  • 10th - 'Natal'
  • 11th - 'Servidor Público'

The month with the highest number of accidents is September.

Time with the highest number of accidents:

  • 1st - 07:00am
  • 2nd - 07:00pm

In [45]:
TP = np.sum(income) # Counting the ones as this is the naive case. Data encoded to numerical values done in the data preprocessing step.
FP = income.count() - TP # Specific to the naive case

TN = 0 # No predicted negatives in the naive case
FN = 0 # No predicted negatives in the naive case

# Calculate accuracy, precision and recall
accuracy = TP / (TP + FP)
precision = TP / (TP + FP)
recall = TP / (TP + FN)

# Calculate F-score using the formula above for beta = 0.5 and correct values for precision and recall.
beta = 0.5
fscore = (((beta*beta) + 1)) * ((precision*recall) / (((beta*beta)*precision) + recall))

# Print the results 
print("Naive Predictor: [Accuracy score: {:.4f}, F-score: {:.4f}]".format(accuracy, fscore))

Naive Predictor: [Accuracy score: 0.2276, F-score: 0.2692]

def train_predict(learner, sample_size, X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test): 
    '''
    inputs:
       - learner: the learning algorithm to be trained and predicted on
       - sample_size: the size of samples (number) to be drawn from training set
       - X_train: features training set
       - y_train: income training set
       - X_test: features testing set
       - y_test: income testing set
    '''
    
    results = {}
    
    # Fit the learner to the training data using slicing with 'sample_size' using .fit(training_features[:], training_labels[:])
    start = time() # Get start time
    learner = learner.fit(X_train[:sample_size], y_train[:sample_size])
    end = time() # Get end time
    
    # Calculate the training time
    results['train_time'] = end - start
        
    # Get the predictions on the test set(X_test),
    #       then get predictions on the first 300 training samples(X_train) using .predict() 
    start = time() # Get start time
    predictions_test = learner.predict(X_test)
    predictions_train = learner.predict(X_train[:300])
    end = time() # Get end time
    
    # Calculate the total prediction time
    results['pred_time'] = end - start
            
    # Compute accuracy on the first 300 training samples which is y_train[:300]
    results['acc_train'] = accuracy_score(y_train[:300], predictions_train )
        
    # Compute accuracy on test set using accuracy_score()
    results['acc_test'] = accuracy_score(y_test, predictions_test)
    
    # Compute F-score on the the first 300 training samples using fbeta_score()
    results['f_train'] = fbeta_score(y_train[:300], predictions_train, beta=0.5)
        
    # Compute F-score on the test set which is y_test
    results['f_test'] = fbeta_score(y_test, predictions_test, beta=0.5)

       
    # Success
    print("{} trained on {} samples.".format(learner.__class__.__name__, sample_size))
        
    # Return the results
    return results

# Initialize the classifier
clf = GradientBoostingClassifier(random_state=42)

# Create the parameters list you wish to tune, using a dictionary if needed.
# parameters = {'parameter_1': [value1, value2], 'parameter_2': [value1, value2]}
parameters = {'min_samples_split':[2, 5, 10], 'min_samples_leaf':[1, 2, 5, 10]}

# Make an fbeta_score scoring object using make_scorer()
scorer = make_scorer(fbeta_score, beta=0.5)

# Perform grid search on the classifier using 'scorer' as the scoring method using GridSearchCV()
grid_obj = GridSearchCV(estimator=clf, param_grid=parameters, scoring=scorer)

# Fit the grid search object to the training data and find the optimal parameters using fit()
grid_fit = grid_obj.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Get the estimator
best_clf = grid_fit.best_estimator_

# Make predictions using the unoptimized and model
predictions = (clf.fit(X_train, y_train)).predict(X_test)
best_predictions = best_clf.predict(X_test)

# Report the before-and-afterscores
print("Unoptimized model\n------")
print("Accuracy score on testing data: {:.4f}".format(accuracy_score(y_test, predictions)))
print("F-score on testing data: {:.4f}".format(fbeta_score(y_test, predictions, beta = 0.5)))
print("\nOptimized Model\n------")
print("Final accuracy score on the testing data: {:.4f}".format(accuracy_score(y_test, best_predictions)))
print("Final F-score on the testing data: {:.4f}".format(fbeta_score(y_test, best_predictions, beta = 0.5)))
